# RxJS and Observables in Angular

RxJS treats **events as streams of values over time** — like a river of data that you can intercept, transform, filter, and combine before it reaches its destination. An Observable is a lazy stream: nothing flows until something subscribes.

```
Promise (single value, eager):        Observable (multiple values, lazy):
  request → [   ] → one response        timer → -0--1--2--3--4-- (infinite)
  (starts immediately when called)       click → ---click--click--- (events)
                                         HTTP  → --------response| (single)
                                         (nothing starts until .subscribe())
```

## The Observable Lifecycle

```
Observable created  →  .subscribe() called  →  values flow  →  complete/error

Creation:     const obs$ = new Observable(subscriber => {
                subscriber.next(1);   // emit value
                subscriber.next(2);
                subscriber.complete(); // stream done
              });

Subscription: obs$.subscribe({
                next:     (v) => console.log(v),  // 1, 2
                error:    (e) => console.error(e),
                complete: ()  => console.log('done')
              });

Convention: variable$ suffix marks an Observable
```

## Common Creation Functions

```typescript
import { of, from, interval, fromEvent, EMPTY, throwError } from 'rxjs';

of(1, 2, 3)                      // emits 1, 2, 3 then completes
from([10, 20, 30])               // same as of but from an array/Promise
from(fetch('/api/data'))         // wraps a Promise
interval(1000)                   // emits 0, 1, 2... every second (never completes)
fromEvent(button, 'click')       // emits on every click
EMPTY                            // completes immediately, emits nothing
throwError(() => new Error('!')) // errors immediately
```

## The Pipe Operator — Transformation Pipeline

```
Observable source
     │
  .pipe(
     │    map(x => x * 2)          ← transform each value
     │    filter(x => x > 5)       ← drop values failing predicate
     │    tap(x => console.log(x)) ← side effect, pass through unchanged
     │    take(3)                  ← complete after 3 values
     │    debounceTime(300)        ← swallow rapid values, emit last after 300ms
     │    distinctUntilChanged()   ← drop consecutive duplicates
  )
     │
  .subscribe(result => ...)
```

## Key Operators

```typescript
import { map, filter, switchMap, mergeMap, concatMap,
         catchError, retry, takeUntil, debounceTime,
         distinctUntilChanged, combineLatest, forkJoin } from 'rxjs/operators';

// switchMap — cancel previous inner, start new (typeahead search)
searchTerm$.pipe(
  debounceTime(300),
  distinctUntilChanged(),
  switchMap(term => this.http.get(`/search?q=${term}`))  // cancels previous request
)

// mergeMap — allow multiple concurrent inners (parallel)
clicks$.pipe(mergeMap(click => this.http.post('/log', click)))

// concatMap — queue inners in order (sequential)
operations$.pipe(concatMap(op => this.http.post('/op', op)))

// catchError — recover from errors
this.http.get('/data').pipe(
  catchError(error => {
    console.error(error);
    return of([]);  // return a fallback Observable
  })
)

// forkJoin — wait for ALL to complete (like Promise.all)
forkJoin([
  this.http.get('/users'),
  this.http.get('/products')
]).subscribe(([users, products]) => ...)

// combineLatest — emit when ANY input emits, with latest from all
combineLatest([user$, settings$]).subscribe(([user, settings]) => ...)
```

## switchMap vs mergeMap vs concatMap

```
   Input:  --A-----B-----C--> (three requests triggered)

   switchMap:                    mergeMap:                  concatMap:
   A starts, then B triggers →   A, B, C all run in         A runs, completes,
   A is CANCELLED.               parallel (concurrent).      then B, then C
   B starts, then C triggers →   All results arrive          (strict ordering).
   B is CANCELLED.               in arrival order.
   Only C's response arrives.    May arrive out of order.

   Use for: typeahead,           Use for: fire-and-forget    Use for: sequential
   live search (latest           analytics events, logging,  operations where
   query wins)                   parallel fetches             order matters
```

## Subscription Management — Memory Leaks

**The single most common source of memory leaks in Angular apps:**

```typescript
// BAD — subscription never cleaned up:
export class MyComponent implements OnInit {
  ngOnInit() {
    this.interval$.subscribe(v => this.value = v);  // LEAK: still runs after destroy
  }
}

// GOOD — Method 1: takeUntil pattern
export class MyComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  private destroy$ = new Subject<void>();

  ngOnInit() {
    this.interval$.pipe(
      takeUntil(this.destroy$)
    ).subscribe(v => this.value = v);
  }

  ngOnDestroy() {
    this.destroy$.next();
    this.destroy$.complete();
  }
}

// GOOD — Method 2: async pipe (auto-manages subscription)
// In template: {{ data$ | async }}
// Angular subscribes on init, unsubscribes on destroy. No manual cleanup needed.

// GOOD — Method 3: takeUntilDestroyed() (Angular 16+)
export class MyComponent {
  private destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);
  ngOnInit() {
    this.interval$.pipe(
      takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef)
    ).subscribe(...);
  }
}
```

## The async Pipe — Preferred Subscription Method

```typescript
// component.ts
@Component({ ... })
export class UserListComponent {
  users$ = this.userService.getUsers();  // Observable, not subscribed yet
  constructor(private userService: UserService) {}
}
```

```html
<!-- template — async pipe subscribes and unsubscribes automatically -->
<ul>
  <li *ngFor="let user of users$ | async">{{ user.name }}</li>
</ul>

<!-- Capture the value to avoid multiple subscriptions: -->
<ng-container *ngIf="users$ | async as users">
  <p>Total: {{ users.length }}</p>
  <li *ngFor="let user of users">{{ user.name }}</li>
</ng-container>
```

## Subject Types

```typescript
import { Subject, BehaviorSubject, ReplaySubject } from 'rxjs';

// Subject — multicasts to current subscribers only
const events$ = new Subject<string>();
events$.next('click');  // only current subscribers receive it

// BehaviorSubject — has current value; new subscribers get latest immediately
const user$ = new BehaviorSubject<User | null>(null);
user$.next(loggedInUser);
user$.getValue();  // synchronously get current value
// New subscriber immediately gets current user (even if subscribed after emit)

// ReplaySubject — replays N past values to new subscribers
const logs$ = new ReplaySubject<string>(5);  // remember last 5
```

## Common Pitfalls
- **Nested .subscribe()** — subscribing inside a subscribe callback. Use switchMap/mergeMap instead.
- **Not unsubscribing** — interval, timer, custom Subject streams run forever. Use async pipe or takeUntil.
- **Multiple subscriptions to the same Observable** — each subscription re-executes the source (HTTP calls fire twice). Use `shareReplay(1)` to multicast.
- **Calling subscribe() in a service** — services usually shouldn't subscribe (no lifecycle to clean up). Return Observables; let components subscribe via async pipe.
- **switchMap on write operations** — cancelling a save/delete request mid-flight leaves the backend in an inconsistent state. Use concatMap or mergeMap for writes.

## Connections
- **angular-services-di** — services return Observables from HttpClient
- **angular-routing** — route guards and resolvers use Observables
- **angular-signals** — signals are Angular's newer reactive primitive, simpler than RxJS for component state

